Q: 1 see Java 2 and Java 5.0, but was there a Java 3 
and 4? And why is it Java 5.0 but not Java 2.0?
 A: The joys of marketing... when the version of Java 
shifted from 1.1 to 1.2, the changes to Java were 50 
dramatic that the marketers decided we needed a whole 
new “name”, 50 they started calling it Java 2, even though 
the actual version of Java was 1.2. But versions 1.3 and 1.4 
were still considered Java 2. There never was a Java 3 or 
4. Beginning with Java version 1.5, the marketers decided 
once again that the changes were 50 dramatic that a 
new name was needed (and most developers agreed), 50 
they looked at the options. The next number in the name 
sequence would be “3”, but calling Java 1.5 Java 3 seemed 
more confusing, 50 they decided to name it Java 5.0 to 
match the “5” in version “1.5”. 
50, the original Java, versions 1.02 (the first official release) 
through 1.1, were just “Java”. Versions 1.2, 1.3, and 1.4 were 
“Java 2”. And beginning with version 1.5, Java is called “Java 
5.0”. But you’11 also see it called “Java 5” (without the “.0”) 
and “Tiger” (its original code-name). We have no idea what 
will happen with the next release...

